At the end of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange fell into the negative
After Tuesday morning&#39;s fall, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Trading in ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trading.
On Tuesday, when trading began, the Prague Stock Exchange resumed its fall of the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time around, the drop is due to falling stocks on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the stabilization plan for the American financial sector, is thus also perceptible here.
Stocks fall in Asia
The Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even if the indices succeeded, during the day, in erasing part of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange&#39;s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later erased some of the losses and narrowed the decline to almost 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent as markets closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange were down more than five percent, but eventually managed to narrow the loss to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
&quot;The hesitation over bailout action in the US will affect financial markets around the world,&quot; observed Joseph Yam, the head of the Hong Kong Currency Board.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, that is to say independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will suffer the consequences.
The bloodbath in US equities
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, to which it should have devoted up to 700 billion dollars (nearly 12 trillion Kč).
The lawmakers thus rejected the call for support for President George Bush&#39;s plan.
According to Bush, the project should resolve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
US equities experienced a bloodbath on Monday and the main equity indices suffered the biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost nearly seven percent, having last suffered such a large drop in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal did not pass, it was in free fall.
Congress gave in: the US government can inject $700 billion into the banks
The leaders of the United States Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the agreement for financial assistance to the American financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers reached a turning point in talks on the adoption of a bailout package in the form of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns) in financial aid to the U.S. financial system .
Success is by no means certain.
Indeed, before being able to publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, the Congressmans must finish a certain number of details of the agreement.
The plan to support the financial system will be examined Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to a vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should constitute a first major psychological factor in reviving the financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market support can be effective, &quot;disillusionment&quot; will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We&#39;ve settled our differing opinions about what form the market stabilization package should take,&quot; Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be taken as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislators met with the American Treasury Minister Henry Paulson, in order to give the bottom of the government a final form.
The latter should buy back, from the financial companies, the unsaleable real estate assets which involve the financial companies in considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still have to pursue this market recovery plan, but I think we&#39;re there,&quot; said Paulson.
A signal for Asian exchanges
The global financial crisis is having a huge impact on falling equity markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are working to get Congress to reach a final agreement on Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trading in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the decision of Congress could affect Monday&#39;s trading.
However, for the moment, it is impossible to specify with certainty when the two Chambers of the American Congress will proceed to the vote, nor if the negotiations are not likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by such and such a problem.
Lawmakers hope it will pass in the coming days.
However, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount intended for using the system should be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion dollars, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels the program is not doing its job, it has the option of blocking the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush hailed progress in negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the option of putting him in a minority.
Despite these modifications, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the purchase of bad real estate titles, the value of which fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
&quot;All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday,&quot; said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President George Bush is himself pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Mr. Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated &quot;the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.&quot;
Limitation of Golden Parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on accountability for the financial program, protecting contributors from losses, agreeing tax breaks, rolling out the plan on the time axis.
The new law also plans to limit the said golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program and it establishes a committee, which will ensure the supervision of the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this and have made significant progress toward an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes help for property owners who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new down payments for mortgages it will buy back, while lowering monthly payments to debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization will be very difficult.
“And this is due to the fact that it is not known what the mechanism and the price of the redemption of the problem assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government,&quot; Marek told the iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or at the beginning of next week, is, according to Marek, not that important.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree, starting this week, that they support this plan and that they will enshrine it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time,&quot; Marek pointed out.
Right-wing populists triumph in Austria, they have 29 percent in total
According to the preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current grand coalition, as well as a notable strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People&#39;s Party (ÖVP), where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly heavy losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at the national level.
According to the preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 percent of the votes, the first political force in the country, however, compared with the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the votes.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent lost almost nine percent of the vote, finished even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major post-war parties; especially for the People&#39;s Party, which called the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the popular party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
But voters visibly chastised them for allowing the government to collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculation about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer, was pronounced.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary council of the party leadership.
Such a development would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election which remains the most probable, namely the renewal of the grand coalition SPÖ and ÖVP.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 percent and BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - the Socialists at the same time expressed the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the popular party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ broke away from it) on a common government, which even provoked sanctions from the European Union .
Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he foresees the return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently is banking on this development.
The last party to gain access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell, among Austrian political parties, from third to fifth position.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four percent limit and entered parliament.
A fight taken to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you how to choose
While almost all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems to follow clearly that it is better to buy only a phone.
Still, there are enough reasons to get a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy an expensive top-of-the-range gramophone for the house to play Maxim Turbulenc&#39;s new album.
On the one hand, such musical products are not released on vinyl, and, from a quality point of view, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
However, if there are vinyl records piled up in your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you at least probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same applies to music on the go, namely compressed music, to put it simply - music in MP3.
Again, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, in the same way that a fan of Pink Floyd would find it hard to stomach earphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
Here are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions that are, of course, unknown to most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the telephone.
Alongside the primary functions, telephone calls and sending SMS, it is capable of playing music and films, of recording the latter, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, up to to be used for navigation.
And if we take into account Smartphones and communicators, you will have in your pocket a small computer.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The greater the number of functions you use, the more the interval between two reloads will be reduced.
And reading music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Mobiles capable of playing music for ten to twelve hours are rare, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary ones) are much more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
This problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, following a reload, of continuous operation for at least 9 hours, including the less efficient ones.
Another problem occurs while saving music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all of them can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
You can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobiles.
With regard to the readers, you do not need, except exception (iPod), any software.
Simply fill the device with music from the computer through the USB connector.
Most mobiles and readers will themselves create a media library classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or else according to the judgment of the user.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a specific device, you are particularly interested in the life of the battery, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of order.
If music is essentially background noise for you and if during the day you are only going to listen to it for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile that plays MP3s.
Virtually all mobiles are capable of this today.
You don&#39;t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or the player is capable of playing.
They all manage to read MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will be in this format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play WMA format music.
AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), meanwhile, is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
All you have to do is visit, from your mobile phone, the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a music mobile.
The offer of the operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in the majority of the cases, to radio tubes quickly made.
The prices aren&#39;t the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by mobile phone, internet or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile with them.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, when you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which practically all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, one can have an already very decent Walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best and best equipped telephones, also provided with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of easy ordering.
Really anyone manages to ensure the control of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the control&#39;s resemblance to that of a cassette player, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly plugged in mobile internet, followed by an immense data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (eg Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models basically only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive even manage with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman mobiles instead (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of control approaches that of a freestanding MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the furthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by a MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering practically the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we are still missing something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, many times, on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher here than in the rest of the Union, has also confirmed this.
Thus, following the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks a competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that greatly exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly declared that in the Czech Republic there is no longer any place for another operator, agrees with the operators.
It is probably true that a traditional operator with his own network apparently does not have much luck (by the way, now he would hardly find frequencies).
Now, there is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which the traditional operators were subsequently also to react.
Yet even before spoilsports such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those we hear at home today were being heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have real success.
We don&#39;t have to look too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let&#39;s add that behind Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which owns, among other things, U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators being the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be efficient, they indeed need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network, which are relatively high.
This is how in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
&quot;Real men choose Mobilking - a carrier they like and can trust,&quot; says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operator of this virtual carrier.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would also work here.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone&#39;s spokesman, doubts: &quot;The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services.&quot;
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
&quot;We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Czechia the negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our zone,&quot; Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favor of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not hidden, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
&quot;We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile ones.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations about this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we managed to make progress in the negotiations,&quot; said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
The future may therefore be promising.
According to unofficial information, it looks like we might be able to welcome the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by complete silence.
&quot;At the moment we do not believe there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us,&quot; mentioned Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with O2&#39;s statement: &quot;We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a basis.&quot;
And she adds: &quot;It is practically impossible that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time frame, we should have a concrete agreement now.&quot;
Vodafone is instead directing its attention to fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says in relation to this: &quot;We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most input from a customer perspective.
Vodafone&#39;s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.&quot;
The responsible authorities: in tune with the operators
The approach of the mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a drop in prices and therefore a drop in their profit.
So why facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to get along like thieves at a fair. The quibble accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, during the creation of the U:fon, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ web pages.
However, today, U:fon lends itself to being used as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented on this: &quot;Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would place high demands on it, and especially its services.&quot;
But given the attitude of mobile operators here, the indifference of Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, it is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
This belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, the latter adopted, faced with this problem, his typical position.
&quot;The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No agreement of this type has been concluded for the moment, because the offer of the potential interested parties did not a priori present sufficient interest for the traditional operators,&quot; specified in answer to our question Kristián Chalupa from the Department of external relations of the ÚOHS.
A statement formulated in this way would not come as a surprise on the part of operators&#39; representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and among other things also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially since Kristián Chalupa adds: &quot;Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a drop in the prices of mobile telephone services.&quot;
However, pushing for an honest functioning of the market and lower prices is apparently not in the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
In the same way, a strictly identical price of gasoline at all service stations is surely due to chance and the hard fight of competition.
“The office has not found any signs of anti-competitive behavior in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, none therefore has a correspondingly increased responsibility for its behavior on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even the telecommunications regulator,&quot; Chaloupa said in his statement.
One of the many points of contention is the interpretation of market dominance.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose another view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator quite logically has a monopoly on its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators obviously proceed in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Placing the blame on the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in communications, by means of which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the matter.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Regrettably, the recently adopted novelization of the telecommunications law did not succeed in enacting an extension of the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This, the representatives of the ÚOHS must know very well, but their interests apparently lie elsewhere.
When no one is watching, it can work
However, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but these are only partly public.
In most cases, it is a question of firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specialized mobile telephone services are thus offered by, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally only reach elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company acts in front of the operator as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large quantity of SIM cards.
As a major customer, she gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
&quot;If what you mention happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would examine and which could lead to a cessation of the collaboration with the company in question,&quot; answered our question relating to this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity did not reach the heads of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible benefits, and, at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: &quot;The law allows such speculations, nevertheless, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, like ordinary customers of mobile operators.
Now, this is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question arises at the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to content itself with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it .
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable drop in the price of services.
However, practically in all the countries where virtual operators appeared, the traditional operators tried, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - too small or even too saturated a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies in developed countries have intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators treat this issue like a hot potato that gets rid of by passing it on to a nearby target.
From the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that the confusion in competences is in these cases more than profitable to them.
But let&#39;s not throw the handle after the ax.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and a virtual operator will soon appear on our premises, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain impassive in the face of rejection (discrimination) from other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theater Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo vocal, a performance with choir and an instrumental version.
Vocals are provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful anthems.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
&quot;From the beginning, I tried to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, have good diction, so that we understand the lyrics well, that they sing simultaneously,&quot; he said. -He specifies.
