Prague public transport (MHD) will introduce the chip in its ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will go down in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers board the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible to about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day or 90-day coupon (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and both have it registered on their smart card at information points and Dopravní podnik offices (l Transport Agency), located at Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy coupons online on the web pages of Dopravní podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people enjoyed the service during the morning.
Those who start using the online store can definitely forget about ticket counters in metro stations, where until now they had to stomp impatiently in long queues in order to obtain paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon on the internet and it will be registered on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
&quot;In these touchpoints, passengers have a counter with trained staff, who will help those interested in purchasing via the internet and, in addition, will register the coupon they have purchased on their card,&quot; says project spokesperson Martin Opatrný.
Alongside the libraries, it will also be possible to register electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these dispensers look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket punching machines, and passengers may have already noticed them at Roztyly, Budějovická, IP Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
&quot;Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty,&quot; Opatrný added.
An automaton will check the coupon instead of the driver
The automatons which will operate from tomorrow are easy to use.
Simply insert the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also around the city.
Namely in suburban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the municipalities of central Bohemia to access the capital.
&quot;In trains integrated in Pražská integrovaná doprava (Prague integrated transport), conductors are equipped with card readers, with the help of which they establish the temporary and zonal validity of coupons;&quot; explained ticket control Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization, which designs Prague public transport timetables.
Suburban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver&#39;s body.
When boarding, it is therefore necessary not only to show the chip card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard in the place indicated on the side of the cash desk.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the registered coupons.
&quot;In case the passenger needs to check the validity of the saved coupons, there is nothing simpler than asking the driver for this information,&quot; Drápal completed.
Passengers who do not take the suburban buses and will not remember the date when the validity of their coupon expires, can rejoin the vending machines, initially used to register the coupons on the card.
It is there, on the screen of the device, that the information concerning the validity of their document will be displayed.
The Sudetenland demanded a referendum in the USA
The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This follows from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly approached the President of the United States with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov pray in the letter to the US President not to allow &quot;šumavská župa&quot; (region of forests in southern Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
&quot;We understand the situation well and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,&quot; is written in the letter, signed &quot;Persons, to whom the fate of Šumava is close to heart&quot;.
Since joining Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - nothing but brutality, callousness, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the President American to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
&quot;We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a State foreign to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies without taking into consideration the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants ,&quot; is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the &quot;Czech oppressors&quot;.
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it does illustrate the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans should at least foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic will arise, very few of them admit to such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Great Britain would obtain for the Sudetenland some type of autonomy.
Others believed they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German from České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp in the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
&quot;They believed that when they got back home, the Czech would benefit them,&quot; says Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed, according to him, that, following the Beneš Decrees, they would be expelled from the republic.
