Questions that arise after the accident: Are the stewards in the coach illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance bus is prohibited
In the context of the tragic accident of the Student Agency coach near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can move around inside the coach during the journey.
&quot;If one wanted to respect the law strictly and formally, the activity of a steward is against the law on road traffic,&quot; said spokesman for the Ministry of Transport Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, during which a 22-year-old hostess perished, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck which crossed the path of the bus.
The young girl was at this time unfortunately seated next to the driver, on the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the coach can have an accident, or even brake suddenly, also when the steward is serving coffee or distributing newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is according to its specifications equipped with standing room or not.
If this standing equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing room; which was confirmed to Aktuálně.cz by company director Radim Jančura.
&quot;It&#39;s a matter that we have discussed with the ministry and initially they are banning any movement of passengers.
Then they canceled it and we got that passengers can go to the toilet during the trip as long as they have their own seat,&quot; he revealed his position.
The law ignores the steward
&quot;There is no unambiguous legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal prescription deals with this role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement prohibits the carrier from offering services either.
The law on road transport knows only the term receiver of the vehicle; it does not define his rights and duties,&quot; adds spokesman Hanzelka more ambiguously.
Josef Pokorný, the director of the road vehicle traffic department, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the problem.
&quot;It all depends on whether the coach has standing room permission in its homologation.
It&#39;s all in there,&quot; he said.
Coaches are divided into city, where there is standing room and a limited maximum speed, intercity with standing room and a higher permitted speed, and long-distance coaches with no standing room with the highest permitted maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like on the plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Hořín, an expert at BESIP (road traffic safety) in transport safety, does not see the displacement of on-board stewards as a major problem.
&quot;During regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service in airplanes.
