Rats have feelings too
A rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean that it also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how could we verify that he experiences the same thing when he behaves in the same way as us?
In the online magazine &quot;Edge&quot; contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question &quot;What do you think is true without being able to have proof of it?&quot;
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else have not yet been able to prove, just as you cannot prove that other human beings have a awareness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and we approach the questions of feeling or in general of consciousness, we penetrate into difficult terrain because the Hardware does not correspond.
When a rat is faced with danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it plays dead, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I don&#39;t believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuitry almost always associated with human consciousness includes the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and executive and executive functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and seems to be entirely absent in other beings.
At the very least, then, for those aspects of our consciousness which depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the awareness of who we are, and the ability to foresee and decide, it is reasonable to suppose that the human being is even differentiated from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could reside in the linguistic nature of Man: a large part of his existence being linked to language, this often means that his conscience depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, language would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, however produced, would probably be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, can neither be measured nor, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed based on our own experience, then its observation poses big problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could examine animal consciousness processes without considering their content, and that is exactly what has happened in studies of primate short-term memory, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, one concentrates more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two may or may not be identical.
Curiously, this approach also underlines the weight of the prefrontal cortex in achieving visualization.
But what does this mean for the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a brain aware of its own activity.
What we designate as &quot;fear&quot; is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as the reactions of the body) monopolizes living memory.
Observed in this way, emotions are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and particularly humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our voluble nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities arise in the regions of bodily sensation in the Cortex and the brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep who, however, concentrates more on the brainstem.
As this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could very well take part in transversal sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is undemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in humans and in rats is also likely to be felt as such in both cases: how could one verify whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similar way?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if it feels fear?
In my eyes, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Certainly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brainstems, cockroaches on the other hand do not even have a brain.
But is the brainstem the source of sensations?
And even if we could prove this for humans: how could we demonstrate it in rats?
I believe rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have feelings.
But I don&#39;t know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are presumably completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuitry and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is poignant on the nervous level insofar as the same thing is gauged in rats and in humans.
As I don&#39;t explore language and consciousness in rats, nor sensations, I don&#39;t know if they exist.
You could judge this as short term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly bumping into a wall.
I am indeed an emotional pragmatist.
