In a City Apart, Pride and the Trials of Black Life
Hidden away in its sprawling park development, a few miles from sunny, shiny, giant Orlando, lies a quiet little town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are born.
&quot;Eatonville, the first all-black city to integrate, the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, this description she made in 1935, is not so easy to do today.&quot; The city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skinned people, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guavas, two schools and no jails.&quot;
It has now become a city of pilgrimage
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the Zora Festival, held each year in Eatonville, to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in many ways, the town she describes—became touristy thanks to its inclusion in The Depression-era Federal Writers&#39; Project&#39;s Florida Travel Guide—remains a place of its own.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston said that rural black Florida people were often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who &quot;knowing us so little, does not know what he loses&quot;.
Even though this is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who has also invoked an open dialogue on the subject of race, many here remain cautious about the gaze of the &#39;foreign.
&quot;We&#39;re very careful about how to tell the story,&quot; said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and the town&#39;s oldest parishioner.
&quot;It has to be realistic.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It represents both a historical model of black empowerment as well as a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a focal point but also an example of black Southern rural culture – sometimes scorned, other times acclaimed – that recalls the birth of American slavery.
Which would explain why the residents are both proud and protective.
The interest in Eatonville&#39;s image started with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt, dialect-filled books such as &quot;Mules and Men&quot; (1935) and &quot;Their Eyes Were Watching God&quot; (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guidebook transformed this city, located just off Route 17, a route through often-forgotten central Florida that culminates in a chapter of black history and human drama.
Bold as a bass drum in life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store owned by Eatonville&#39;s first mayor, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was later divided into several private parts.
&quot;past the road on the left&quot;, she writes, &quot;you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its well-preserved gardens and play areas which Howard Miller has always taken care of, although he can barely read and write.
She also mentioned Widow Dash&#39;s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn &quot;sells all kinds of drinks and anything that can be used by people passing through.
So, in just a hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not like that.
It wasn&#39;t actually a portrait that everyone liked.
Zora described reality well,&quot; said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson&#39;s young daughters whom Hurston immortalized, citing the colorless songs sung by men who praised their beauty.
She added, &quot;some people didn&#39;t like it.&quot;
Hurston is always remembered as a lively and eccentric person, who returned frequently after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually drove into town unannounced in a big Chevrolet, a cigarette in his mouth and wearing slacks here, where even today we are proud of traditional dress.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin recounted, while many laughed at her.
&quot;People were always happy to see Zora,&quot; he said.
But he further adds, rocking in his chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was likely baptized, that “she never stayed too long.”
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of production.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in some grave in Fort Pierce, Fla, where she lived.
In Eatonville, no major commemoration or plaque for the general public.
I don&#39;t think they understood the contribution or the legacy she offered to the world,&quot; said Valerie Boyd, author of &quot;Wrapped in Rainbows,&quot; a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A crucial moment came in the 1980s.
Orange County public officials wanted to run a five-lane freeway through town, replacing Kennedy Boulevard, the community&#39;s main two-lane street.
Orlando&#39;s development has already pushed Interstate 4 to the west corner of the city.
The proposal came as Eatonville was just recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among many other things, ended the community&#39;s relatively idyllic isolation.
In the 1950s, the race-mixing dispute brought hatred to the doorsteps of the community.
&quot;At that time, a bunch of young white people would come and throw oranges or objects at people sitting on the side,&quot; Franklin said.
“one lady even died.”
They threw a watermelon out of their car.&quot;
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston cast doubt on the Supreme Court&#39;s motion for forced integration, defining its decision in Brown v. Board of Education &quot;insulting rather than glorifying my race&quot;.
Residents now claim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, while positive in some aspects, has diluted Eatonville&#39;s cohesion and weakened the confidence of young people.
&quot;Black children used to be kissed - I remember well - we kissed our master in the morning, and in the evening too&quot; declared NY Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins as well as chief director of Safeguarding of the Community of Eatonville, a non-profit group.
This lasted, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
“You don&#39;t kiss your white teacher because he&#39;s white – I mean there&#39;s a cultural dividing line here,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, by the way, has created space for many more Zora Neale Hurston—black writers, actors, and artists who have gone beyond prejudice, such as her, armed with a joyous confidence of her own. and guidelines such as: &quot;how can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!&quot;
That beats me.&quot;
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited Hurston&#39;s unmarked grave and began to struggle to revive his reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography on Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, a true bestseller, thus reintroduced her to the American canons.
The freeway project came just as Eatonville&#39;s most famous girl had regained her allure.
And this time, Hurston&#39;s old neighbors see her as a savior.
The community began to organize a Hurston festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences that this highway would cause.
Hundreds of fans came to the festival&#39;s inauguration two years later, and many return in January to commemorate it.
After many years, the county rejected the highway proposal.
&quot;The fiasco of the five-lane highway, extremely fast, a real civic pride,&quot; said Melle. Natiri.
Miss Boyd summed it all up stating that &quot;Zora saved Eatonville&quot;.
The victory against the highway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non-residents, like Rachelle Munson, an attorney who has attended our church since 1993, began to come in large numbers, and residents began to reconsider the past.
Eatonville has been listed as a historic town since 1998.
A mono-themed library (renamed of course Hurston) opened in 2006, on a magnificent, repaved Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly for Florida: six miles from Orlando, it can at any time consider itself a back street on a rainy summer day, small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(nowadays 90 percent are black)
Outsiders who come to learn about Eatonville&#39;s history, its raison d&#39;être, are still treated with caution.
You have to ask permission for most interviews, and some things - like the walls of the old church in Eatonville, painted by the white man, depicting black men in the fields - shouldn&#39;t be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Miss Jones, a spunky teacher and a fan of bright red, still fear their island community will be misunderstood.
However, with the expansion of the Hurston Festival, a certain level of local pride has emerged.
Young people in particular tend to view Eatonville as Hurston viewed his entire race: beautiful, problematic and all, neither better nor worse, but as proud, creative, hard-working, crazy and mixed as any other ethnic and racial group in America.
It is indeed genuine civic affection in the voice of Mr. Franklin&#39;s nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the forces. of Police, who need additional forces.
And even for the younger ones, like 11-year-old Alondra and Alexia Kenon, twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned the Eatonville description correctly.
&quot;Most people passing through this area will think, &#39;oh, this town is nothing compared to others&#39;,&quot; Alondra Kenon said after mass last Sunday.
But if you stop and take the time to contemplate the history, it&#39;s a very beautiful city.&quot;
