William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (who died on September 25) states that &quot;in 1946, he had resumed his studies in economic history at Oxford, and in 1950 became a member of Houblon-Norma research, while he was doing a BSc, an MA and a PhD&quot;.
This is from the author&#39;s letter to Woodruff in Beyond Nab End, but it is not correct.
From 1946 to 1953 he was professor of economic history at the University of Nottingham, and was at the same time completing a PhD thesis on the British plastics industry, under the supervision of Professor JD Chambers; it was then published in 1958 as The British Rubber Industry.
In the 50s and 51s in the United States, he studied at Houblon Norman, and in the summer of 1952, at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for Illinois.
Why Woodruff chose to hide this part of his past remains unknown.
