&quot;I photograph the master offstage to capture elements of his character&quot; Günther Bauer - Photographer
Neither heels nor New Year&#39;s clothing.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, released from all tensions to obtain the relaxed aspect of the man or the woman.
On one side the artist.
On the other, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in those moments unknown to the general public, where we discover through intimate gestures and stolen glances artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in &quot;Flamenco - people&quot; the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the program of the Month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition &quot;reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day&quot;, explains the creator, who clarifies that &quot;Flamenco - people&quot; &quot;can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the viewer realizes that these are not typical images of performers on stage.
These people photographed &quot;in the street&quot; are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you should not take pictures on stage.
They have their own personality and character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera personal moments of flamenco stars&quot;.
With the festival &quot;Chant populaire des Mines&quot;, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, bring to mind classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: &quot;Music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day &quot;.
It is not the dancing or singing per se, but the personality and character of the performer that captivates the audience with their art.
The search for the essential and for magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from around seventy artists photographed.
The project turned into a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in a book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer&#39;s passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the &quot;Portraits of Old Sportsmen&quot; (&quot;SportARTproject&quot;).
Although the concepts are different in &quot;Flamenco - people&quot;, the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a more or less long moment.
I believe that in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that you sometimes don&#39;t know or who only give you a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.&quot;
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco which is entitled &quot;Flamenco - people&quot;, is exhibited at the Gallery El Fotómata, located at number 20 rue de la Mata (street parallel to the Peupleraie d&#39;Hercule) which will be open until October 16.
