Second assault for Honda&#39;s super sales
In November Honda will start marketing the second generation of the Jazz model.
If its predecessor already had a good habitability, this new MPV has an even larger interior space.
Added to this are some refined mechanics, which increase driving comfort and save more fuel.
An evolution in the face of a revolution.
So this is the second generation of the Honda Jazz.
Although aesthetically the new Honda Jazz presents a line very similar to the previous model, the changes introduced in this monovolume are numerous.
Among them there is an innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new engines.
However, before looking at the new model, it should be pointed out that this new Honda Jazz arrives six years after the first generation was put on the market.
First of all we observe that Honda has renovated this model in a shorter time than that of other manufacturers.
Although in Europe the Honda Jazz is less known, this model is a sales phenomenon in other markets.
This is the case in Japan, where the Honda Jazz was the most sold car in 2002 and also in 2008.
Specifically in Japan, almost a million Honda Jazz have been sold since its launch.
The Old Continent, with more or less one million cars sold in six years, is in second place.
However, Honda claims that this new Jazz will allow it to increase its sales in Europe.
Thus, while in 2007 the Japanese brand marketed 83,000 Honda Jazz, in 2009 it plans to sell 100,000, which would represent a sales growth of 17% on the European market.
On the Spanish market, Honda has marketed 8,000 Jazz since 2002, which represents 6.7% of Honda sales in Spain.
The managers of the Spanish subsidiary hope to sell 2,000 Jazz in one year.
It is precisely the release of the new Jazz that will allow Honda to largely compensate for the drop in sales in Spain.
Indeed, those responsible for the brand hope to end the year with sales of 22,000 cars, ie 4,000 cars less than in 2007, ie a drop in sales of 16%.
Thanks to this increase in sales, Honda increased its market share in Spain, reaching a market share of 1.8%, compared to 1.6% last year.
The Japanese brand also hopes to achieve a 2% market share in 2010.
Honda hopes to get that market share when the new model comes out.
This is the Insight, a hybrid with five doors and a compact size - 4.37 meters in length - on which the Japanese company hopes to market nearly 200,000 cars per year worldwide.
Depending on the markets and according to the Japanese manufacturer&#39;s estimates, 50% of Insight sales will be in the United States, while the remaining half will be split between the Old Container and Japan.
The commercial launch of the Insight is scheduled for the first three months of next year, after its presentation to the public in January in Valencia.
Compared to the first generation, the new Jazz increases its dimensions.
Its length reaches 3.90 meters (five centimeters more), its width 1.69 meters (two centimeters more) and the distance between its axes is 2.50 meters which represents an increase of five centimeters.
On the other hand, the height does not change, i.e. 1.52 meters.
The dimensions increase and so does the interior space.
This gain is due, on the one hand, to the introduction of a new platform and, on the other, to the introduction of a petrol reserve in a central position, a solution also adopted for the Honda Jazz.
Likewise, the capacity of the trunk - which has a double bottom system - can hold up to 399 litres, 19 liters more capacity than the trunk of the first generation.
It should be noted that these dimensions are those of the version with a 1.4L engine, since the trunk capacity of the Honda Jazz 1.2L is 379 liters.
The other innovation - in addition to exterior elements such as rear lights or the panoramic roof - is improved access to the rear seats.
The doors that give access to the rear seats have an opening angle of 80 degrees, compared to the rear doors of the first Jazz which opened with an angle of 67 degrees.
The engines are also new on this second generation of the Jazz.
At the start of its marketing, this small model will be equipped with two gasoline engines of 1.2 and 1.4 liters.
Both engines feature i-VTEC technology which reduces fuel consumption and CO2 emissions, makes the engine more powerful and increases engine speed.
The first 1.2-liter engine develops 90 horsepower at 6,000 rpm and 114 Nm of torque at 4,900 rpm.
This thruster - which on the previous Jazz reached 78 horsepower - has a fuel consumption of 5.3 liters per 100 km and emissions of 125 grams of CO2.
Compared to the previous thruster, which on the previous generation reached 83 horsepower, now reached 100 horsepower.
This 100 horsepower Honda Jazz 1.4L has a combined consumption of 5.4 liters per 100 km and emissions of 128 grams of CO2.
