The Interview - Blood Made Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he won back the public trust that had been seriously shaken by the tainted blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood supplies managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Service were contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the discontent of the public, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, an inquiry which aimed to shed light on the circumstances which led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations so that such a disaster does not happen again.
While Judge Krever was late in submitting his report, some provinces then set up a committee with the objective of planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and Canadian Blood Services to supply all the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
By dint of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field during the years that followed, we regained the confidence of the public&quot;, she says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that &quot;trust is something extremely fragile&quot;.
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing in Europe the outbreak of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one who has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
&quot;And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We then relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and that a serious illness may result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are instituted.
In April 1999, therefore, blood was refused from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
However, a few years ago, it was demonstrated beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that we applied made sense.&quot;
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NAT), which allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against it. the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have made it possible to shorten the silent period, which extends between the moment when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We have thus substantially reduced the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements have considerably reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health,” says the CEO of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You have to be constantly vigilant,” continues Dr. Décary before emphasizing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also plan for a sufficient supply.
&quot;The needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences for the network of blood donors, which only includes on average 3% of Quebecers who are eligible to donate blood.
Anyone in good health, aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is rife, they will be excluded for a one year period.
“With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer give blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today&#39;s life is so hectic, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,&quot; laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burned.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is teeming with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious illnesses, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to collect more than a thousand a year.
We should start offering them for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
&quot;Several mothers are disappointed not to be able to have access to it&quot;, because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
