Charest bets on the North
The Prime Minister does not rule out calling an election before the end of the year
As soon as the general council of the Liberal Party ended, Jean Charest went yesterday to Jean-Talon, in Quebec, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (on the left), is trying to get elected on the occasion of the by-election today.
&quot;Pushing back the limits of our last great northern border&quot;: this is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force while remaining in broad outline, at the end of the General Council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis , yesterday.
Behind him, during his speech, was projected a sort of Image Mill.
Looped, on three huge screens, spectacular shots of hydroelectric dams, mining, Quebec seen by &quot;Google Maps&quot;, maps, etc.
Great means as in the election period.
In a press conference, moreover, the Prime Minister refused to rule out that he would call the elections this fall, even if he pointed out that his schedule was very busy.
The &quot;Plan Nord&quot; is the fourth part of a &quot;vision&quot; that the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a &quot;new economic space&quot;, which includes a labor agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the speeches of the Prime Minister recently, the opening of the North - the northern territory at the 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, confined himself to explaining why the North was &quot;a jewel with immense potential&quot;, but did not give a deadline, investment amounts, or specific priority in future projects.
At most a few avenues of what could be further developed: in particular hydroelectricity, the forest, but above all the mining sector, boosted by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains &quot;nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamond&quot;, according to Mr. Charest&#39;s enumeration.
This “territory twice the size of France”, “it is with us, it is in Quebec.
Not only is it with us, but it is in us”, he insisted, as if to show that he was seeking a national founding myth.
Quebec has built a lot in its relationship with the North, he pointed out: the gold rush in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
&quot;It&#39;s ours, it&#39;s our future,&quot; he added, after pausing theatrically to gaze at the huge map behind him.
The North, 70% of Quebec territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, said the Prime Minister during the press briefing.
“It is a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a border line on which there has been no agreement for a very long time and, when the opportunity arises, I reiterate this position on behalf of the government,” he said.
Moreover, &quot;with climate change, we have to rethink our vision of the North,&quot; he said of the Northwest Passage, which will be open all year round due to melting ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister considers that occupying the territory is a duty.
What about the inhabitants of the territory, the First Nations and the Inuit?
The Premier said that the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, especially young people.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former PQ MP for Ungava), have already begun consultations with some thirty communities.
An interdepartmental committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has an important place has begun work.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a big meeting, &quot;not necessarily a summit&quot;, but a moment when &quot;we will give ourselves a common vision&quot;.
The development of the North would also be done in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Plan Nord will be &quot;concerted, orderly and respectful of the environment&quot;, he promised.
Jean Charest described this &quot;vision&quot; as being in continuity with that of Liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
&quot;Like the Liberals who came before us, we thought differently to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development.&quot;
This was also one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began Friday with a large cocktail party to mark the 50th anniversary of the arrival of Jean Lesage at the head of the party.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes to rename the Beauharnois power plant as the Adélard-Godbout dam.
&quot;From Godbout, who created Hydro-Québec, to Lesage, who made the Quiet Revolution and the nationalization of hydroelectricity, to Bourassa, who made James Bay, our party knew how to forge the future&quot;, declared Jean Charest .
In a press briefing, he invoked another reference, a conservative one, the &quot;Roads to the North&quot; program of John Diefenbaker, prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
Addressing the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Mr. Charest pointed out that its commissioning was scheduled for 2012.
&quot;It stays between us there, but I plan to be there,&quot; he told his activists, prompting loud applause from them.
Indeed, the Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no election in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of calling a ballot this fall, which the law allow.
He points out that his schedule is however full, in particular by a mission of the council of the federation in China and a Quebec-New York summit.
The General Council of the weekend provided the Liberal leader with a platform containing nationalist resolutions, in particular &quot;constitutional aspirations&quot; which passed like a letter in the mail: the PLQ in particular demands recognition of the &quot;specificity of Quebec&quot; in the Constitution.
He also wants Quebec to appoint members of the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission and for them to have the right to veto decisions made in Quebec.
On the opposition side, the broad lines of the Plan Nord were greeted with skepticism.
The PQ leader, Pauline Marois, brought out the Nord-du-Québec Development Policy that the Landry government had launched in 2001.
According to her, the Liberal government, when it came to power in 2003, gave up applying it.
