Free Opinion - Barrick Gold&#39;s Orwellian Discourse
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, executive vice-president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, he claims that the world&#39;s largest gold company has filed a six million libel suit against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house in a bid to launch a &quot;transparent public debate&quot;. .
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation suits, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets. of mining.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to look into the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the facts before public opinion.
Contrary to what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, the debates in Canada are normally made by the exchange of ideas and not by beatings with truncheons.
It was therefore enough for the mining company to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the financing of independent research teams which could have shed light on the question. .
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects out of hand the petitions and letters of support to the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both demand &quot;public&quot; debate while disregarding the opinions of that same public?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word refers only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so above all because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in what many perceive as a SLAPP (continuing the &quot;public debate&quot;, Barrick Gold has just elsewhere to file a formal notice to the authors of Noir Canada ordering them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver&#39;s surreal rhetoric, the Barrick Gold lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the search for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, en bloc, the right to citation of credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the wealthy companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated lawsuits, who will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic world, to which we belong, has a long history of managing debates and disagreements and resolving conflicts.
Barrick Gold&#39;s outsized pursuit makes it clear that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for academia, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of frivolous prosecution.
Wall Street Bailout - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the 700 billion US dollar plan aimed at curbing the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months must still be ratified by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: better control by elected officials of its application, new mechanisms aimed at ensuring the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to inspect the salaries paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
&quot;We have made great strides toward an agreement that will work in the marketplace,&quot; Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
“Everything was done in a way to shield the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” the Democrat explained.
&quot;That&#39;s the bottom line: If we don&#39;t do this, the trauma, chaos, and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense,&quot; Republican Judd Gregg said.
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last hours for fear of the effect that another failure would have on the mood of investors.
The time limit that we agreed to was the opening of the markets this morning.
Belatedly associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the American presidential election showed themselves to be rather favorable to the agreement, without however failing to express their dissatisfaction that we are obliged to come to this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has claimed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, in particular that aimed at allowing owners to keep their homes and that on the salary of the leaders of companies rescued by the State.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary,” he commented on American television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: &quot;I would like to see the details, but I hope so.&quot;
&quot;The outline that I&#39;ve read [shows] that it&#39;s something that we&#39;re all going to have to digest and move on with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers&#39; money the bad debts, risky and unsellable assets of American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgage loans before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (ABCP) and lead to a freeze of liquidity and the rout of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who had derailed the first draft agreement last week.
This impasse is believed to have been broken since the Democrats agreed that certain &quot;toxic&quot; assets of ailing companies should only be insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to smooth things over for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision stipulating that if the government had to bear losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover his bet.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which another 100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be ratified by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain stakes in the rescued companies which will earn him dividends in the event of a profit and which he can resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying the procedures for foreclosures concerning the housing attached to the mortgages concerned by this plan, as well as setting limits on the remuneration and severance pay paid to the managers of the companies affected.
The plan&#39;s architects would like to see it voted on by the House of Representatives today, and by the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite their best efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be given the green light.
Voices have indeed continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
&quot;Obviously Washington can&#39;t hear you,&quot; Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
&quot;Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of taking advantage of the taxpayers”.
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed &quot;the caucus of skeptics&quot;, Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
&quot;Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us saying: Congress is asked not to rush and to carefully consider the way forward,&quot; he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up acquiring its competitor in the midst of the sinking since it lost 2 billion euros. euros (2.9 billion US) in the subprime mortgage crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
&quot;It&#39;s not wasted money,&quot; Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In exchange, we get a right to vote in the bank and some influence.
It&#39;s just something that savers and households appreciate now that times are going to be uncertain.&quot;
Meanwhile, across the Channel, the British government appeared to be nationalizing another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all the loans in progress at the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
Her beauty with azure eyes was for a long time her trump card, some would say her weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, his sensitivity and a talent that flowed from source will also have distanced him from the register of power that gives birth to the real sacred monsters.
But what a great long-distance runner!
Paul Newman, who died on Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer on his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema from the boom years.
Less monumental than Brando, whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a sort of rival on screen, more cautious in his acting, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the bursting of dramatic conventions.
Mixed bloods often make beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German-Jewish father and a Hungarian-born mother.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, ultimate mark of quality.
Because in him was projected a whole country in love with the self-made man, the combatant of the Pacific war, wounded in combat, who in the early 1950s studied drama at Yale then attended the Actor&#39;s Studio in New York, before to triumph in the theatre, on television, soon in the cinema.
This same man who campaigned for civil rights was also the racing driver who finished second in the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 1979, doubled as a sex symbol, although member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
Also disappear with him the gray areas of this secret star, discreet, committed, allergic to the splinters of show business, whose enigma we will not have completely pierced.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the term.
The disappearance of Paul Newman has given moviegoers vertigo this weekend, as his great roles clash on the black screen of memories.
More than half a century of a perpetually changing seventh American art scrolls through him.
The memory of the charming cowboy of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Pussy on a Hot Roof adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958, comes back to haunt.
Closer to us (1990), we evoke his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all its promises.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somebody Up There Likes Me (Marked by hatred), by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, resumed after his death, which really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic thug in the brilliant The Sting (The Scam), Oscar for best film in 1973.
Bitter and vengeful billiard player in Robert Rossen&#39;s magnificent The Hustler (1961), he would take up the character on his return in Martin Scorsese&#39;s The Color of Money, which in 1987 earned him his only Oscar out of nine nominations.
This face through the ages was him.
Him again.
The eras jostle through his career.
Young people know him especially through George Roy Hill&#39;s cult Slap Shot (1977), in Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy by the Coen brothers.
With a final role as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes in 2003, the circle was complete.
Contrary to several cinema legends who gave up the profession quite early, Newman will have remained in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its gold, its splendor and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, &quot;as a living challenge to the&quot; underplaying &quot;judging his performances too strong.
The profession has not always been kind to the handsome Paul Newman, whose roles fell into his mouth for a long time.
However, he played less often the young first than the marginalized: neurotics, alcoholics, bastards or despairing, whose perfect features reflected the excesses and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known facets of his true modest sensibility.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a fine feminine portrait of melancholy.
He who lost his son Scott by overdose dedicated his film Harry and Son to him in 1984, a work of modesty and sadness.
Among the rain of tributes that swept over Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade in arms Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) affirmed, very saddened: &quot;His presence made my life and this country better.&quot;
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant traits of the late actor.
Beyond his legendary career, also fades a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the excesses of Hollywood.
We will have seen many of his smiles enthroned on jars of vinaigrette, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging the process to be in rather bad taste, although gag at the start.
