What could Zuschlag &amp; Compagnie manufacture in their invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, having caused particularly significant damage. Other charges were brought against them, such as forgery and use of forgery.
According to the prosecution, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the state and the municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand into the pockets of certain people.
Their method, also made public by the authorities in charge of the investigation, was to receive the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing expense invoices, behind which no real service was provided and thus the associations never respected their commitments. .
According to the indictment, many of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they made the seals at Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that were going to appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the rounds in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the statement of the latter, he had to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they produced the other invoices that they were going to submit, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor, as well as of the Capital Municipality to access subsidies.
Most of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drafting the files necessary to obtain the subsidies.
During a &quot;scouting tour&quot;, one of Lados&#39; choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place provided catering for a group of 90 people, members of the Biztos Pont Egyesület association.
However, according to the words of the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövőért foundation, which would later bear the name of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors of form and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there. However, the invoice mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
The imaginative invoice issuers also went overboard when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért, nor that of Hoppá appeared, according to information given to the prosecution.
Győző Farkas, the company&#39;s manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor&#39;s office summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew right away that they were forged documents.
&quot;Our company name and tax number were placed in the wrong place on the stamp.&quot;
He added: &quot;Beyond the form, the fact that according to the invoice, one hundred people stayed there, did not fit either, since this establishment only has eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the invoice also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time.&quot;
Zealous billers also did not inquire about Budapest travel agencies, being among their choice, but only organizing trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
Moreover, as it appeared during the investigation, they also added VAT to these documents, whereas the services relating to travel activities, the destination of which is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices issued in the name of Hotel Révfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company&#39;s services do not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15 %. In addition, hotel employees only issue printed invoices, while fake ones were written by hand.
The prosecutor&#39;s investigation reveals that the &quot;issuers&quot; also made mistakes by mentioning the transport of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not perform, given that its profile was investment advice.
In addition, it is also for formal defects, such as incorrect types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and de Biztos Pont turned out to be false.
As in the case of the Ravenna Bt. company or the Kunfehértó sports camp, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued in their name.
Nor did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation when (in 2001) the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group was supposed to have a meal at their house. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Deliberately established invoices
Another category of invoice issuers are those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány foundation, at the request of the group of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice to the order of the Együtt foundation in Harmadik Évezredért, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was led to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Likewise, cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the order of the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the association Vörösfenyő Egyesület, for an amount of approximately five million HUF, but behind which no benefits were actually provided.
No financial movement took place, either, since the invoices issued were subsequently canceled, but the organizations avoided mentioning this in their accounts.
The next category of billing companies are companies directly related to the defendants.
So, the administrative delegate of the general director of the company Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where he could not be found there, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, this company issued several invoices concerning the sale of computer equipment, for an amount of approximately 18 million HUF.
According to the investigation, this equipment would have been purchased by the company Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since September 14, 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov would also have sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
According to what we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and de Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he pocketed their equivalent value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In reality, none of these companies were functioning, which the accused explains by the fact that they did not receive any work.
He nevertheless used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-defendant as well as drafter of the deeds of foundation of the companies, he established invoices in their names, to the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov gave organizations a total of 15 invoices, issued by the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of 14.2 million HUF.
The prosecution believed that 10% of the sums indicated on the invoices as well as the VAT went into Kubatov&#39;s pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices which were used as part of Biztos Pont&#39;s grant application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied for a grant from the socialist party&#39;s public benefit body, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They obtained this grant for an amount of twice 500,000 HUF, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To prevent this from becoming known, five fictitious invoices received from the company Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, these are the invoices that were found during the search carried out in the office of Árpád Kemecsei, at the Ministry of Education.
During the hearing, some of the defendants will recount the method of production of the invoices, as they had already done before the prosecution previously.
What could be really interesting would be that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confession is not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to recount the finer details, he has yet to do so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or perhaps the socialists would have reached an agreement whereby in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the fifty million HUF, Zusi would carry the blame alone.
Today, the latter is probably upset, since the requests for his placement under house arrest, on the basis of an alleviation of his conditions of detention, continually fall on deaf ears.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of irreparable economic crimes, walk around freely or at least wait in their own homes for the end of the procedure. He does not have this possibility.
The psychology of one-upmanship: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to overspend and overprice the merchandise.
Neurology and economics researchers at New York University have successfully unearthed the neurological and economic underpinnings of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be left behind in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to draw a neurological diagram of this kind of &quot;game&quot; using experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played lotto, while the other group took part in a fun auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the one-third overbid, the assembly below the brainstem, called the striatum, moved from intensively when the game is lost.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the &quot;self-stimulating&quot; mechanism of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained with the escape from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economist members of this group of researchers have pursued financial monitoring analyses.
During these, three groups outbid a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the real value of the product in question, and they thus made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they won the game, then they would receive an additional 15 dollars, as a reward.
While the third group received these 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group also lost this money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the accent was placed in one on victory, while in the other, on failure.
In thus proving the neurologists&#39; hypothesis, the members of the team of players &quot;against failure&quot; were willing to wager higher than those made by the control group and the group &quot;for the victory&quot;.
&quot;These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them only explained the phenomena observed during auctions by the pleasure of winning and the parade in the face of risk.
Only neuroimaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories, now leading to a third explanation.&quot; - noted Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should we consult a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that 100,000 patients are carriers of the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only 7,000 are receiving treatment. This is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and the diseases they cause differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogen genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is anyway recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated food, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become lighter and the urine takes on a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, each year, one million people die of the most serious form of this pathology, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know they are infected with the virus, because the pathogenic gene insidiously destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, along with regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis type C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as you observe symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its purpose is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
