Does the one who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious belief would work as a kind of painkiller, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford carried out an interesting experiment by analyzing at what level belief in God could influence the pain tolerance of human beings.
As part of this bizarre experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also possible to discover that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiments, in which academicians, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment takes place as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshocks is attached to the left hand of the experimental subject.
Researchers asked participants of the experiment to stare intently at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other being the Lady with an Ermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century. .
The researchers behind this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke some sort of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci&#39;s painting, not dissimilar to the first, focused on her soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 four-part electroshocks in succession, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed painting.
Catholics said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary they felt &quot;safe&quot;, as someone who was &quot;taken care of&quot; and they &quot;calmed down, and peace came over them&quot;.
At the sight of the painting with a religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonardo&#39;s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, among atheists, provided you find the appropriate photo.
&quot;We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father, for example,&quot; the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
&quot;The practice of faith should change and in many cases does change our personality,&quot; Wright added.
After these excellent results, only the question remains, what would be the effect on the subjects&#39; pain regulation if believers were shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the sight of a higher quality Virgin Mary bring about better results?
