The intelligent automobile imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, that of bees.
In the amazing project showcased at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees provided the initial strategic idea for Nissan engineers to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle sensors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-controlling robotic system, type BR23C, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the final objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval in shape, which in reality looks a lot like our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and relations department technological public of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a vital role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, engineers came up with the idea of the laser range finder.
This identifies obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms it into an avoidance maneuver.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it by an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Unlike any existing system today, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
&quot;If it were not so, the mini robot car could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle&quot; - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process should reflect what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
The process should happen in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, difference cannot go up, down, or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees have to avoid other bees, in our case we could only use the rotary movement, the acceleration as well as the deceleration as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries which are lighter and have a larger power pack, which makes their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is essential, not the processing of data, and even less the capacity to store.
This mechanism must process only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. This way it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
You don&#39;t need memory with a capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instantaneous avoidance. According to Nissan&#39;s estimates, this system will make its way into mass-produced cars within the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to their destination avoiding obstacles in their path.
