Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export selling prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to those of July 2008, while compared to those of a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial producer prices increased by 0.7 percent compared to those of the previous month, and by 3.2 percent compared to those of the previous year. .
Domestic industrial selling prices increased only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic selling prices in the processing industry sectors increased only marginally by 0.1 percent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the manufacture of leather goods and footwear (2.8 per cent), led by the manufacture of bags and belts with an increase monthly increase of 4.6 percent, followed by footwear production with a 2.5 percent monthly increase.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly increase in the prices of the chemical products and materials manufacturing sector (1.6 percent).
Deflation resulted in the petroleum processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and appliance manufacturing (0.9 per cent) sectors, as well as a minimal increase in the wood processing (0.1 percent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase of between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent a significant weight in national industrial exploitation, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas implemented by the authorities since July 1.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sale of the processing sectors, the prices of the petroleum processing sector experienced the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metal products manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 percent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 percent. .
Price decreases occurred in the production of textiles and textile products (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the rise in prices varied between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices rose by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 percent higher than a year earlier.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, the investment profit initiating sectors showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods-producing sectors, prices rose 0.3 percent, while those in the energy-producing and materials-for-further-processing sectors were unchanged from the previous month. .
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the greatest increase was observed in the sectors of production of energy and materials intended for further processing (16.8 percent).
In the sectors producing consumer goods, an inflation of 6.8 percent was measured, while for the profit-initiating sectors a decrease of 1.4 percent.
Industrial sector export selling prices, in HUF terms, rose 1.1 percent in August from the previous month, while falling 3.9 percent year-on-year.
In one month, our national means of payment has weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro, and by 7.1 percent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it has strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
