A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information concerning his drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market is spiraling out of control.
“There are data protection programs that bind the use of information regarding the prescription of drugs, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it&#39;s like entrusting your chicken coop to a fox&quot; - reminded Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage drug prescriptions, to the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the capital insured in the event of damage depend on the state of health of the client who presents himself, and if they consider that the risk is too great, they do not insure him. not even.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after seeing the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much less expensive procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies the data concerning the person&#39;s drug purchases in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers from and what is his state of health.
For example, if that person regularly buys high doses of a cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine at the same time a risk coefficient, so there is not much left for the insurer to do apart from the paperwork. However, tiny issues can still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, certain mixtures can be used against migraine or against hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Societies have developed in research and data analysis. They must ask the patient&#39;s permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failings in the past.
Recently, some companies are also processing the results of laboratory analyzes and linking them with data on drug consumption. In this way, they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients&#39; health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and monitoring its use is becoming more and more difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope only extends to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on expanding the authorities&#39; circle of control over companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard recognizes that this is not enough and that is why he has developed his program even further, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question to know if the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
So and ultimately, the hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
