Mp3 player pointed out, they put hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is announced by the European Commission, which, in a press release issued in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
&quot; from this scientific report - we read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day per week, risk permanent hearing loss.”
&quot;I am concerned that such a large number of young people, who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume, may unknowingly damage their hearing beyond repair,&quot; says Meglena Kuneva.
&quot;According to the scientific data - continues the EU official - this is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most is to educate consumers and make this information public.
In addition, we need to re-examine the existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can keep up with new technologies&quot;
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
&quot;The scientists - concludes the EU executive - confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now examine with Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be adopted to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100Db, but concern is growing about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to effectively limit these data by resorting to solutions such as reducing the levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits relating to the maximum noise level allowed on the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for prolonged periods of time risk permanent hearing loss after 5 years.
This concerns 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU
