The superglue for walking on walls.
Overcome the laws of gravity with super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the objective of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring barely 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers succeeded in keeping a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
THE STUDY- The American journal Science published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nanotubes.
&quot;The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti.&quot; Explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs which ensure the animal has a perfect grip.
Tests carried out on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it &quot;detaches easily from the wall&quot; explains Liming Dai, researcher from the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
WALK ON WALLS? –&quot;this material could be used as a temporary adhesive&quot; adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers are thinking of a much less fascinating use such as connecting electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes conduct heat and electrical current.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, in California, is also dedicated to the search for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American journal American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive made up of microfibers like hair, which cleans itself of dust during movement over a surface to guarantee perfect and constant adhesion.
Medicines: never with fruit juices.
Watch out for grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in summer because they are thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, if associated with certain vital medicines, alter their absorption, amplifying or decreasing their effectiveness, depending on the case, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society underway in Philadelphia, he launched a new alarm: all it takes is a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice to reduce the absorption of certain vital drugs, nullifying their beneficial effects and putting the health of patients at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-staminal and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
RISK DRUGS - It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which gave the news in a newsletter dated two years ago, alerting doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger deriving from this mix and to be careful what you drink, if you take medication such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT JUST GRAPEFRUIT- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contain substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
From there, the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the department of pharmacology of the Public University of Milan: &quot;these discoveries are in general, immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies which will have to, if necessary, change the informative notes of the medications.
It is always advisable to read the illustrative papers of the drugs that one takes, and, if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to address clearly to the doctor or the pharmacist&quot; underlined the expert to Ansa agency.
