Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market is not experiencing a crisis
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants&#39; union, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
&quot;The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that the families of origin have to bear - explains the head of the study office from Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand from students has distorted the market so much that a process of generalized increase has begun even for residents.
In most cases, offers to rent additionally have a series of violations: contracts of free type, unregistered, without limit of rent, subleases.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax taxation are necessary to calm prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it costs around 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (Bande Nere area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room around 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), they ask about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euro for a single) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can only save if you move away to peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed you need 300/400 euros, for a single you spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for a bed, it takes 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, in cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by students from outside the community, there is a further anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old Cinema Paradiso, the cities elect the historic halls.
Historic movie theaters are closing in favor of Multiplexes.
&quot;A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it&#39;s like a face without eyes&quot;
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial towns,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of large multi-screens, and the death of single-screen consumption in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems to us to be inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, these are often historic places loaded with memories, &quot;it&#39;s as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of a journey and so many emotions&quot; observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film which won Tornatore 20 years ago the first Oscar as well as the Cannes Jury Grand Prix, and which told of the poetry of a provincial theater and the nostalgia of a way of living cinema, perhaps lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, say it all: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the cinemas in the main cities that have mainly paid the costs: 10 fewer than Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine leads with 82 single-screen cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is indeed the three Italian regions which have registered the most new multi-screen cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy over the past five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
&quot;Italian exploitation has developed in an irrational way&quot;, observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, &quot;it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those which already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these attendees are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of the credit in favor of traders: the antecedent debt of the State is around 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect the existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote cinemas mono rooms in historic centers and on the outskirts.
Among the standards planned, there are tax facilitation measures in favor of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone, and will have special rates for parking and in certain parkings.
&quot;It&#39;s an initiative that I like&quot; observes Giuseppe Tornatore &quot;and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna&#39;s example by implementing other measures.
It is however obvious that, to contrast the superpower of multiplexes, traditional cinemas must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today&#39;s public is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema de Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make &quot;New Cinema Paradiso&quot; to which I already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I turn to the other side so as not to see the panels blackened by dust.
