When the energy is born from the waves, now the big ones are launched.
Here is a disproportionate deposit which occupies more than 70% of the surface of the planet and now the large world energy companies are in the process of discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that giants like Chevron have laid their eyes on, and are now trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil are giving a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world&#39;s electricity needs could be covered by sea swell exploitation systems.
This quantity would be double that produced by nuclear power plants.
And in addition, there would be currents and tides..
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more candidates among these companies, which have always been dedicated to traditional energy, are betting on marine energy.
&quot;Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies - a spokesman for a company associated with the American oil colossus told the Wall Street Journal - and is evaluating the possibilities of cooperating with us&quot;.
The cooperation in question relates to the obtaining of a permit deliberated by the US Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially if we consider that precisely in Alaska, the United States continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations
In addition to Chevron, there is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which are running the ocean power route, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are not are known, indicate, according to observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, because ocean energy does not dispel fears about environmental impact.
At present, systems like those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create any major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a greater ecological impact.
&quot;And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys linked to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the mud up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure from the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through submarine cables.
Right now we have four such systems in the planning stage, pending one federal approval, and some of the power could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already generating power for a shopping center and parking lot using six underwater turbines from New York&#39;s East River.
The movement of the water during the tides causes the blades of the turbines to turn, creating a rotary motion that powers a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Of particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electric Power Research, deserves at this time, the potential of the tides.
Although an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, with others, look towards the coasts, invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and foresees investments up to 35 million in 2009.
